1. Statistical Learning Methods

  1. An inflexible method would work better if the number of predictors p was extremely large, and the number of observations n was small. If we were to use a flexible method, we would risk overfitting the data, which would cause the model to describe the random error instead of the underlying relationship of the data. Therefore, an inflexible method is better as this would minimise this risk.

  2. If the sample size of n is extremely large, and the number of predictors p is small, it is better to use a flexible statistical learning method. By using a flexible method, the model would accurately fit a wider range of possible shapes of f. As the data set includes a very large number of observations n, it is likely to obtain an accurate estimate of f. Therefore, the use of a flexible method would be better.

  3. If the relationship between the predictors p and the response is highly non-linear then it is better to use a non-linear model. As the data is highly non-linear, a flexible method would more accurately fit this data and provide a more accurate result.

  4. If the standard deviation of the error terms is extremely high, then it is better to use an inflexible method to fit this data. As the variance of the errors in the data is extremely high, we would risk overfitting the data if we used a flexible statistical learning method. For this reason, it is better to use an inflexible method to minimise the amount of noise described by the high variance of the error terms.

2. Bayes’ Rule

Based on the given data-set of 20 samples, we can calculate:

P(Play Golf = yes) = 10/20 = 0.5

P(Play Golf = no) = 10/20 = 0.5

P(Temperature = hot) = 12/20 = 0.6

P(Temperature = cool) = 8/20 = 0.4

P(Temperature = hot | Play Golf = yes) = 5/10 = 0.5

P(Temperature = cool | Play Golf = yes) = 5/10 = 0.5

P(Temperature = hot | Play Golf = no) = 7/10 = 0.7

P(Temperature = cool | Play Golf = no) = 3/10 = 0.3

According to Bayes’ Rule, it can be calculated that:

P(Play Golf = yes | Temperature = hot) = (0.5 * 0.5) / 0.6 = 0.416

P(Play Golf = no | Temperature = hot) = (0.7 * 0.5) / 0.6 = 0.583

P(Play Golf = yes | Temperature = cool) = (0.5 * 0.5) / 0.4 = 0.625

P(Play Golf = no | Temperature = cool) = (0.3 * 0.5) / 0.4 = 0.375

Based on the scatter-plots above, the most useful variables for predicting gas mileage (mpg) due to a potential relationship between the variable and mpg are: acceleration, displacement, weight, horsepower and year. The variables which are not so useful and have no significant relationship are: cylinders and origin.

From the scatter-graphs against mpg, we can see that:

As mpg increases acceleration increases; As mpg increases displacement decreases; As mpg increases weight decreases; As mpg increases horsepower decreases.

There is also a weak relationship between mpg and year such that as mpg increases, year also tends to increase.

For mpg and cylinders, it is difficult to gain any conclusions from the scatter-plot. For mpg and origin, there is an indication of origin increasing as year increases, however I would not deem this to be a significant or very useful observation compared to others. Therefore, predicting mpg based on the relationship mpg has with cylinders or origin is not as useful as the other above mentioned variables.

#4. Linear Regression

horsempg <- data.frame(Auto$mpg, Auto$horsepower)
lm.fit <- lm(mpg~horsepower, data = Auto)
summary(lm.fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = mpg ~ horsepower, data = Auto)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -13.5710  -3.2592  -0.3435   2.7630  16.9240 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 39.935861   0.717499   55.66   <2e-16 ***
## horsepower  -0.157845   0.006446  -24.49   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 4.906 on 390 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.6059, Adjusted R-squared:  0.6049 
## F-statistic: 599.7 on 1 and 390 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

  1. The results of the linear regression model describe a large t-value and a very small p-value. Therefore we are able to reject the null hypothesis and declare a relationship between mpg and horsepower.

  2. The relationship between the predictor and the response is very significant as it is close to 0. The significance code indicates this as it shows thre stars ’***’ indicating high significance.

  3. The relationship between the predictor and the response is negative, as the B1 coefficient is negative, indicating that the slope of the regression line is negative.

predict(lm.fit, newdata = data.frame(horsepower=89))
##        1 
## 25.88768
predict(lm.fit,newdata=data.frame(horsepower=89), interval = "confidence")
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 25.88768 25.36257 26.41279
predict(lm.fit,newdata=data.frame(horsepower=89), interval = "prediction")
##        fit      lwr    upr
## 1 25.88768 16.22836 35.547

The predicted mpg associated with a horsepower of 89 is 25.88768.

The associated 99% confidence interval is 25.88768(fit), 25.36257(lwr), 26.41279(upr).

The associated 99% prediction interval is 25.88768(fit), 16.22836(lwr), 35.547(upr).

plot(Auto$horsepower, Auto$mpg, col=c("red","blue"), pch = c("+", "*"), xlab = "horsepower", ylab = "mpg",
     main = "Plot of horsepower and mpg")

legend("topright", pch =c("+", "*"),
       col = c("red", "blue"),
       legend = c("horsepower", "mpg"))

abline(lm.fit)

plot(Auto$horsepower, Auto$mpg, col = c("green", "orange"), pch = c("+", "*"), xlab = "horsepower", ylab = "mpg",
     main = "Plot of horsepower and mpg")

abline(lm.fit, lwd = 2)

powermpg = data.frame(horsepower = seq(46, 230))

p_conf <- predict(lm.fit, interval = "confidence", newdata = powermpg)
p_pred <- predict(lm.fit, interval = "prediction", newdata = powermpg)

lines(powermpg$horsepower, p_conf[,"lwr"], col="red", type="b", pch="+")
lines(powermpg$horsepower, p_conf[,"upr"], col="red", type="b", pch="+")
lines(powermpg$horsepower, p_pred[,"upr"], col="blue", type="b", pch="*")
lines(powermpg$horsepower, p_pred[,"lwr"], col="blue", type="b", pch="*")

legend("topright",
       pch=c("+", "*"),
       col=c("green","orange","red","blue"),
       legend = c("horsepower","mpg", "confidence","prediction"))

auroc_value <- auroc@y.values[[1]]

auroc_value
## [1] 0.6038194

The Auroc value for glm.ohum.pred model is 0.6038194.

The glm.pred model (which uses all the features) achieves the best accuracy amongst all three models. The Auroc value for the glm.pred model is the highest at 0.7977778, compared to the other two models, which are 0.6038194 when using only humidity as a predictor, and 0.7527431, when using only temperature as a predictor. In addition, the ROC curve for the glm.pred model (red curve) is the model with the closest curve to the upper left corner, which is the ideal point for a ROC curve. The other two curves, (green and blue) are further away from the upper left corner of the graph, indicating lower classification accuracy compared to the red curve.

6. Resampling Methods

Although both models will either underfit (model A) or overfit (model B) the data, I would consider model A as the better model. Model A is a quadratic model, therefore a curve will be produced for the training data which attempts to fit the cubic model. As a result, model A is a likely to fit the test data better, as model B will mostly likely overfit the data. Model B is more complex and flexible, this means the bias wil be lower, however the variance will be greater resulting most likely in overfitting. As a result, I would expect to get a more accurate prediction on the test data with model A, compared to model B.

set.seed(235)
x = 12 +rnorm(400)
y = 1 - x + 4*x^2 - 5*x^3 + rnorm(400)
plot(x,y, col=c("red","blue"), pch = c("+", "*"))

From the scatterplot, I can see that as x increases, y decreases. There is a strong negative correlation amongst the data.

The adjusted mean squared error rate (MSE) using the 10 k-fold CV method is 1.075833.

The results when the seed is 34, and when it is 68 are not the same. This is because the set.seed function picks a different set of random numbers each time a new seed is set. Therefore, the results will never be the same when using different seeds to generate output, but results do remain repeatable if the same seed is used without change (i.e setting the seed to 34 and not changing it).

The second model which is a fourth degree polynomial has the smallest LOOCV and 10-fold CV error in question c. This is what I expected as I anticipated that this model would overfit the data, therefore seemingly producing a lower error rate. The first model, which is a second degree polynomial, has a very high error rate compared to the second model, and this is mostly likely because it is underfitting the data.

The coefficient estimates and statistical significance of the coefficient estimates for poly(x, 3)1, poly(x, 3)2 and poly(x, 2)1, poly(x, 2)2 are the same for both model A and the cubic model. This suggests that we would have had a good result had we used Model A without knowing the function was cubic. Nevertheless, by including the third degree polynomial estimate in our model, we get a better result as this is what our actual data represents.

The LOOCV error for model A was 115.8634, and the LOOCV error for the cubic model is 0.9650645. The 10-fold CV error for model A was 112.5722, and the 10-fold CV error for the cubic model is 0.9615719. Overall, the LOOCV error and the 10-fold CV error was significantly lower for the cubic model, compared to model A which was quadratic. This is most likely due to the fact that model A is underfitting the data, and therefore does not output accurate predictions on the test data as the model has not learnt enough in the training stage on the training data.
